## Context

Remark R1-12's core concern is not the removal counts (0284 delivered those)
but the *errors* of the two exact dedup passes — WP-vs-published pairs that
escape both. 0276 writes that discussion; per the number-provenance norm it
can only quote pipeline-traceable numbers. A read-only pilot (2026-07-22,
doudou, current catalogs) validated the design and produced these estimates:

**False negatives (residual duplicates in refined_works, 30,987 docs):**
- Exact-title + same first-author-lastname + different year (gap ≤5): 315
  pairs. Sampled composition: ~half COP27 multi-journal editorial variants,
  ~half genuine version pairs (SSRN/NBER/preprint → journal, dataset/chapter
  editions) — the referee's predicted class, ≈0.5% of the corpus.
- Adding fuzzy-title (Jaccard ≥0.7) same-author pairs: 927 distinct docs
  (3.0%) in any candidate family — upper bound; the fuzzy tier is dominated
  by the COP27 cluster (137 docs, already flagged in `near_duplicate_group`)
  and by report series/editions that are NOT duplicates (OECD annual series,
  World Bank country reports).
- Author-aware dedup (referee's suggestion) would target the 315-pair tier;
  the C-finding below shows first-author metadata is noisy (name-order swaps
  across sources), so it needs normalized author matching.

**False positives:**
- DOI pass (833 removals): 113 of 797 groups have divergent titles; most are
  benign (subtitle truncation, book/chapter, translations). ~40 groups with
  near-zero title overlap are OpenAlex DOI collisions between unrelated works
  (~5% of removals, ~0.13% of corpus).
- Title+year pass (154 removals): 33 of 129 groups carry different author
  lastnames, but most are name-order artifacts (e.g. given/family swapped);
  genuine wrong merges ≈5–10 groups, concentrated where the key degrades:
  generic titles with EMPTY year ("climate finance|" merged 6 distinct
  works). The empty-year key merges same-title works across all unknown
  years — identifiable weakness worth fixing or footnoting.

